26 (f) (1) In accordance with regulations adopted by the Board, a licensed
27 physician may delegate duties to a registered cardiovascular invasive specialist assisting
28 in the physician’s performance of fluoroscopy if:
29 (i) The delegated duties are limited to a cardiac catheterization
30 procedure performed in a hospital cardiac catheterization laboratory;
31 (ii) The physician is physically present and personally directs each
32 act performed by the registered cardiovascular invasive specialist;
33 (iii) The registered cardiovascular invasive specialist has completed
34 the training and education and has the experience required by regulations adopted by the
35 Board; and

6 SENATE BILL 915
1 (iv) The hospital in which the cardiac catheterization laboratory is
2 located has verified and documented that the registered cardiovascular invasive specialist
3 has completed the training and education and has the experience required by regulations
4 adopted by the Board.
5 (2) The hospital in which the cardiac catheterization laboratory is located
6 and the physician delegating duties to a registered cardiovascular invasive specialist under
7 this subsection are responsible for ensuring that all requirements of this subsection are
8 met for each procedure.
9 (3) A disciplinary panel may impose a civil penalty of up to $5,000 for each
10 instance of a hospital’s failure to comply with the requirements of this subsection.
11 (g) (1) (i) In this subsection the following words have the meanings
12 indicated.
13 (ii) “Direct supervision” means oversight exercised by a delegating
14 physician who is:
15 1. Personally treating the patient;
16 2. In the same medical office as the patient and the
17 supervised medical graduate; and
18 3. Immediately available to provide assistance and guidance
19 to the supervised medical graduate for the duration of the completion of a delegated duty.
20 (iii) “Supervised medical graduate” means an individual who:
21 1. Has a degree of:
22 A. Doctor of medicine from a medical school that is accredited
23 by an accrediting organization that the Board recognizes in its regulations; or
24 B. Doctor of osteopathy from a school of osteopathy in the
25 United States, its territories or possessions, Puerto Rico, or Canada that has standards for
26 graduation equivalent to those established by the American Osteopathic Association; and
27 2. Has passed parts 1 and 2 of:
28 A. The United States Medical Licensing Examination; or
29 B. The Comprehensive Osteopathic Medical Licensing
30 Examination of the United States.

