20 PROCEDURE OR THE USE OF THE EQUIPMENT;
21 (26) FAILS TO COOPERATE WITH A LAWFUL INVESTIGATION
22 CONDUCTED BY THE BOARD OR A DISCIPLINARY PANEL;
23 (27) FAILS TO PRACTICE UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF A LICENSED
24 PHYSICIAN OR LICENSED RADIOGRAPHER OR VIOLATES A SUPERVISORY ORDER OF
25 A SUPERVISING PHYSICIAN OR SUPERVISING RADIOGRAPHER; OR
26 (28) FAILS TO COMPLETE A CRIMINAL HISTORY RECORDS CHECK
27 UNDER § 14–308.1 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
28 (B) EXCEPT AS OTHERWISE PROVIDED IN THE ADMINISTRATIVE
29 PROCEDURE ACT, BEFORE THE BOARD OR A DISCIPLINARY PANEL TAKES ANY
30 ACTION UNDER SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION, THE BOARD OR A DISCIPLINARY
31 PANEL SHALL GIVE THE INDIVIDUAL AGAINST WHOM THE ACTION IS
32 CONTEMPLATED AN OPPORTUNITY FOR A HEARING BEFORE THE BOARD OR THE

SENATE BILL 915 17
1 DISCIPLINARY PANEL IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE HEARING REQUIREMENTS OF §
2 14–405 OF THIS TITLE.
3 (C) (1) ON THE FILING OF CERTIFIED DOCKET ENTRIES WITH THE BOARD
4 BY THE OFFICE OF THE ATTORNEY GENERAL, A DISCIPLINARY PANEL SHALL ORDER
5 THE SUSPENSION OF A REGISTRATION IF THE REGISTRANT IS CONVICTED OF OR
6 PLEADS GUILTY OR NOLO CONTENDERE WITH RESPECT TO A CRIME INVOLVING
7 MORAL TURPITUDE, WHETHER OR NOT ANY APPEAL OR OTHER PROCEEDING IS
8 PENDING TO HAVE THE CONVICTION OR PLEA SET ASIDE.
9 (2) AFTER COMPLETION OF THE APPELLATE PROCESS, IF THE
10 CONVICTION HAS NOT BEEN REVERSED OR THE PLEA HAS NOT BEEN SET ASIDE WITH
11 RESPECT TO A CRIME INVOLVING MORAL TURPITUDE, A DISCIPLINARY PANEL
12 SHALL ORDER THE REVOCATION OF A REGISTRATION ON THE CERTIFICATION BY
13 THE OFFICE OF THE ATTORNEY GENERAL.
14 (D) IF, AFTER A HEARING UNDER § 14–405 OF THIS TITLE, A DISCIPLINARY
15 PANEL FINDS THAT THERE ARE GROUNDS UNDER SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION
16 TO SUSPEND OR REVOKE A REGISTRATION, TO REPRIMAND A REGISTRANT, OR TO
17 PLACE A REGISTRANT ON PROBATION, THE DISCIPLINARY PANEL MAY IMPOSE A
18 FINE SUBJECT TO THE BOARD’S REGULATIONS IN ADDITION TO SUSPENDING OR
19 REVOKING THE LICENSE, REPRIMANDING THE REGISTRANT, OR PLACING THE
20 REGISTRANT ON PROBATION.
21 (E) IN ADDITION TO ANY SANCTION AUTHORIZED UNDER THIS SECTION, A
22 DISCIPLINARY PANEL MAY REQUIRE A REGISTRANT TO COMPLY WITH SPECIFIED
23 TERMS AND CONDITIONS DETERMINED BY THE DISCIPLINARY PANEL.
24 14–602.
25 (a) Unless authorized to practice medicine under this title, a person may not
26 represent to the public, by description of services, methods, or procedures, or otherwise,
27 that the person is authorized to practice medicine in this State.
28 (b) Except as otherwise provided in this article, a person may not use the words
29 or terms “Dr.”, “doctor”, “physician”, “D.O.”, or “M.D.” with the intent to represent that the
30 person practices medicine, unless the person is:
31 (1) Licensed to practice medicine under this title;
32 (2) A physician licensed by and residing in another jurisdiction, while
33 engaging in consultation with a physician licensed in this State;
34 (3) A physician employed in the service of the federal government while
35 practicing within the scope of the employment;

18 SENATE BILL 915
1 (4) A physician who resides in and is licensed to practice medicine by any
2 state adjoining this State and whose practice extends into this State;
3 (5) An individual in a postgraduate medical program that is accredited by
4 an accrediting organization recognized by the Board in regulations while the individual is
5 practicing medicine in the program; or
6 (6) A licensee who is on emeritus status under § 14–320.1 of this title,
7 provided that the licensee does not represent to the public that the licensee is authorized
8 to practice medicine in the State.
9 (c) An unlicensed individual who acts under § 14–302 [or], § 14–306, § 14–306.1,
10 § 14–306.2, OR § 14–306.3 of this title may use the word “physician” together with another
11 word to describe the occupation of the individual as in phrases such as “physician’s
12 assistant” or “physician’s aide”.
13 15–302.1.
14 (c) (1) Subject to paragraph (2) of this subsection and subsection (d) of this
15 section and except as provided in subsection (e) of this section, a physician assistant may
16 perform advanced duties in a practice setting that is not an exempt facility only after the
17 physician assistant obtains Board approval of the advanced duty under the collaboration
18 agreement.
19 (2) [(i) Subject to subparagraph (ii) of this paragraph, a] A physician
20 assistant may perform X–ray duties [authorized under § 14–306(e) of this article] in the
21 medical office of a patient care team physician [only after the] IF:
22 (I) THE PHYSICIAN ASSISTANT HAS COMPLETED A COURSE
23 THAT INCLUDES RADIOGRAPHIC STUDIES OF THE EXTREMITIES OF AT LEAST 20
24 SEPARATE PATIENTS;
25 (II) THE X–RAYS ARE LIMITED TO THE EXTREMITIES;
26 (III) THE X–RAYS ARE PERFORMED UNDER THE DIRECT
27 SUPERVISION OF A COLLABORATING PHYSICIAN OR RADIOLOGIST;
28 (IV) THE X–RAYS ARE PERFORMED USING A MINI C–ARM OR A
29 SIMILAR LOW–LEVEL RADIATION MACHINE TO PERFORM NONFLUOROSCOPIC X–RAY
30 PROCEDURES; AND
31 (V) THE physician assistant obtains Board approval of the X–ray
32 duty AS AN ADVANCED DUTY under the collaboration agreement.

SENATE BILL 915 19
1 [(ii) A collaboration agreement may authorize the delegation of X–ray
2 duties limited to nonfluoroscopic X–ray procedures of the extremities, anterior–posterior
3 and lateral, not including the head.]
4 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
5 October 1, 2026.
Approved:
